ch-based-refinement/external/OpenLtm-main/docs/README.md\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/OpenLtm-main/docs/03-architecture.md\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/OpenLtm-main/docs/internal/ROADMAP.md\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/OpenLtm-main/docs/internal/UX-SPEC.md\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/OpenLtm-main/docs/internal/PRD.md\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/OpenLtm-main/docs/internal/README.md\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/OpenLtm-main/docs/internal/DB-SPEC.md","metadata":{"count":16,"truncated":false},"title":"specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/OpenLtm-main","time":{"start":1780925325581,"end":1780925325613}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_006a219cdef8e912016a26c38d670081919ea7b03c2aa6ad91"}},"id":"prt_ea76be10a001jhlPxemFIHnbbp","sessionID":"ses_158954ac9ffePahLx5YfsvlJLH","messageID":"msg_ea76b9c5c001CtqQNn32Dw96BB"}}
{"type":"step_finish","timestamp":1780925326072,"sessionID":"ses_158954ac9ffePahLx5YfsvlJLH","part":{"id":"prt_ea76be2ee001DdjOd7ctDU9H2U","reason":"tool-calls","snapshot":"248e36d5f60fe802865cc2ec6f43f109b747a691","messageID":"msg_ea76b9c5c001CtqQNn32Dw96BB","sessionID":"ses_158954ac9ffePahLx5YfsvlJLH","type":"step-finish","tokens":{"total":55493,"input":14033,"output":475,"reasoning":25,"cache":{"write":0,"read":40960}},"cost":0}}
{"type":"step_start","timestamp":1780925328219,"sessionID":"ses_158954ac9ffePahLx5YfsvlJLH","part":{"id":"prt_ea76beb59001O3tkw2xnEWH1it","messageID":"msg_ea76be466001gwQJbddIXqivKi","sessionID":"ses_158954ac9ffePahLx5YfsvlJLH","snapshot":"aaf23726d5f1425327c6920350f3da2bf10d8ddd","type":"step-start"}}
{"type":"text","timestamp":1780925341807,"sessionID":"ses_158954ac9ffePahLx5YfsvlJLH","part":{"id":"prt_ea76bff85001lQLdjGjfgYvvUd","messageID":"msg_ea76be466001gwQJbddIXqivKi","sessionID":"ses_158954ac9ffePahLx5YfsvlJLH","type":"text","text":"I found no doc file named specifically for janitor, but broader architecture docs discuss decay/materialization, pending proposals, and janitor direction; I’m reading those exact sections and schema migrations for status fields.","time":{"start":1780925333381,"end":1780925341803},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"msg_0765f137e9f02783016a26c3955d3081919e5b7c939a226e63","phase":"commentary"}}}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1780925341853,"sessionID":"ses_158954ac9ffePahLx5YfsvlJLH","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_4E8uVzdRkU6lGOZAGSWD6UnJ","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/OpenLtm-main/docs/02-how-it-works.md","offset":58,"limit":34},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/OpenLtm-main/docs/02-how-it-works.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n58: ## Memory decay\n59: \n60: Memories have half-lives based on importance. Stale knowledge fades; critical knowledge never does.\n61: \n62: | Importance | Half-Life | Behavior |\n63: |:----------:|:---------:|----------|\n64: | 5 | Forever | Never decays. Injected every session. |\n65: | 4 | 180 days | Long-lived architectural decisions |\n66: | 3 | 90 days | Standard patterns and workflows |\n67: | 2 | 30 days | Short-lived context |\n68: | 1 | 14 days | Ephemeral — fades fast if not accessed |\n69: \n70: The score formula:\n71: \n72: ```\n73: score = importance × confidence × decay_factor\n74: ```\n75: \n76: A memory's `decay_factor` shrinks toward 0 as it ages past its half-life. Below 0.25, it's **soft-deprecated** — still returned by `recall` if you ask explicitly, but no longer auto-injected at session start.\n77: \n78: This is intentional. A gotcha you never revisited for six months probably no longer applies. If you want it permanent, set `importance: 5`. If you're not sure, set `importance: 3` and let it ride.\n79: \n80: ---\n81: \n82: ## Project structure\n83: \n84: ```\n85: src/                  MCP server, DB layer, embeddings, graph traversal\n86: hooks/src/            4 Claude Code hooks (SessionStart, UpdateContext, EvaluateSession, PreCompact) + 1 git hook (GitCommit)\n87: hooks/lib/            Shared hook utilities (resolveProject, llmExtract)\n88: hooks/bin/            run-hook.sh — bun resolver wrapper for stripped-PATH environments\n89: hooks/hooks.json      Claude Code hook registrations (auto-wired on install)\n90: commands/             4 slash commands\n91: skills/               5 Claude Code skills\n\n(Showing lines 58-91 of 109. Use offset=92 to continue.)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"## Memory decay\n\nMemories have half-lives based on importance. Stale knowledge fades; critical knowledge never does.\n\n| Importance | Half-Life | Behavior |\n|:----------:|:---------:|----------|\n| 5 | Forever | Never decays. Injected every session. |\n| 4 | 180 days | Long-lived architectural decisions |\n| 3 | 90 days | Standard patterns and workflows |\n| 2 | 30 days | Short-lived context |\n| 1 | 14 days | Ephemeral — fades fast if not accessed |\n\nThe score formula:\n\n```\nscore = importance × confidence × decay_factor\n```\n\nA memory's `decay_factor` shrinks toward 0 as it ages past its half-life. Below 0.25, it's **soft-deprecated** — still returned by `recall` if you ask explicitly, but no longer auto-injected at session start.\n","truncated":true,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/OpenLtm-main/docs/02-how-it-works.md","text":"## Memory decay\n\nMemories have half-lives based on importance. Stale knowledge fades; critical knowledge never does.\n\n| Importance | Half-Life | Behavior |\n|:----------:|:---------:|----------|\n| 5 | Forever | Never decays. Injected every session. |\n| 4 | 180 days | Long-lived architectural decisions |\n| 3 | 90 days | Standard patterns and workflows |\n| 2 | 30 days | Short-lived context |\n| 1 | 14 days | Ephemeral — fades fast if not accessed |\n\nThe score formula:\n\n```\nscore = importance × confidence × decay_factor\n```\n\nA memory's `decay_factor` shrinks toward 0 as it ages past its half-life. Below 0.25, it's **soft-deprecated** — still returned by `recall` if you ask explicitly, but no longer auto-injected at session start.\n\nThis is intentional. A gotcha you never revisited for six months probably no longer applies. If you want it permanent, set `importance: 5`. If you're not sure, set `importance: 3` and let it ride.\n\n---\n\n## Project structure\n\n```\nsrc/                  MCP server, DB layer, embeddings, graph traversal\nhooks/src/            4 Claude Code hooks (SessionStart, UpdateContext, EvaluateSession, PreCompact) + 1 git hook (GitCommit)\nhooks/lib/            Shared hook utilities (resolveProject, llmExtract)\nhooks/bin/            run-hook.sh — bun resolver wrapper for stripped-PATH environments\nhooks/hooks.json      Claude Code hook registrations (auto-wired on install)\ncommands/             4 slash commands\nskills/               5 Claude Code skills","lineStart":58,"lineEnd":91,"totalLines":109,"truncated":true}},"title":"specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/OpenLtm-main/docs/02-how-it-works.md","time":{"start":1780925341832,"end":1780925341851}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_0765f137e9f02783016a26c39dab4c8191bd86884e2913a167"}},"id":"prt_ea76c2074001wuIR16ooH0rZl6","sessionID":"ses_158954ac9ffePahLx5YfsvlJLH","messageID":"msg_ea76be466001gwQJbddIXqivKi"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1780925341861,"sessionID":"ses_158954ac9ffePahLx5YfsvlJLH","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_nm4A96ZPyt1WpuSAZcMcQtWU","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/OpenLtm-main/docs/03-architecture.md","offset":300,"limit":70},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/OpenLtm-main/docs/03-architecture.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n300: `src/shared-db.ts`. WAL mode is enabled for read-during-write concurrency.\n301: \n302: ### 5.1 Tables\n303: \n304: | Table | Purpose | Lifecycle |\n305: |-------|---------|-----------|\n306: | `memories` | Long-term, durable insights (decisions, gotchas, patterns, etc.). Global or project-scoped. | Permanent unless soft-deleted via `status` |\n307: | `context_items` | Short-term, per-project context. The 4 PRD-defined types: goal, decision, progress, gotcha. | Mixed: progress trimmed to last 20; goal replaced; decision/gotcha permanent |\n308: | `tags` | Tag dictionary (unique names). | Auto-created on use |\n309: | `memory_tags` | M:N join — memory ↔ tag. | Cascading on memory delete |\n310: | `memory_relations` | Knowledge graph edges between memories with typed relationship. | Cascading on memory delete |\n311: | `memories_fts` | FTS5 virtual table mirroring `memories.content`. | Maintained by triggers (insert/update/delete) |\n312: | `settings` | Key-value config for janitor / provider settings. | Manual or migration-managed |\n313: \n314: ### 5.2 `memories` — key columns\n315: \n316: | Column | Purpose |\n317: |--------|---------|\n318: | `id` | Primary key, surrogate `INTEGER` |\n319: | `content` | The memory text. Subject to redaction on write. |\n320: | `category` | One of: `preference`, `architecture`, `gotcha`, `pattern`, `workflow`, `constraint` |\n321: | `importance` | 1–5; `5` opts a global memory into every-session injection |\n322: | `confidence` | 0.0–1.0; reserved for janitor / promotion logic |\n323: | `project_scope` | NULL = global; else project_name (joined with registry) |\n324: | `dedup_key` | UNIQUE; prevents repeated learns of the same fact |\n325: | `status` | `active` / `pending` / `deprecated` / `superseded` — soft-delete + supersession |\n326: | `embedding` | Float32 BLOB; semantic fallback vector. Stripped from MCP responses (would balloon to ~260 KB). |\n327: | `last_used_at`, `last_recalled_at`, `recall_count` | Decay inputs |\n328: | `superseded_by`, `superseded_at` | Pointer to the memory that replaced this one (audit trail) |\n329: | `workspace_id`, `agent_id` | T16 multi-agent metadata; indexed |\n330: \n331: ### 5.3 `context_items` — key columns\n332: \n333: | Column | Purpose |\n334: |--------|---------|\n335: | `project_name` | Foreign-keyed by name to the registry |\n336: | `type` | `goal` / `decision` / `progress` / `gotcha` |\n337: | `content` | Free text |\n338: | `permanent` | 1 for decision/gotcha; 0 for goal/progress |\n339: | `memory_id` | Optional link back to a promoted global memory |\n340: | `status` | `active` / `pending_promotion` / `promoted` |\n341: \n342: ### 5.4 FTS5 setup\n343: \n344: - `memories_fts` is a `content='memories'` external-content FTS5 virtual table.\n345:   Triggers (`memories_ai`, `memories_au`, `memories_ad`) keep the index in sync on\n346:   insert/update/delete.\n347: - Recall path: parameterised `MATCH` query against `memories_fts`, joined back to\n348:   `memories` for category/project/importance filters and decay scoring.\n349: - BM25 ranking is the default; the recall engine post-multiplies by importance and\n350:   decay factors before returning top-N.\n351: \n352: ### 5.5 Decay model (current)\n353: \n354: The current implementation applies decay at recall time, not as a stored score.\n355: \n356: - **Inputs:** `last_recalled_at`, `recall_count`, `importance`, `created_at`.\n357: - **Rule sketch:**\n358:   - If `importance == 5`, no decay.\n359:   - If memory has not been recalled in 90+ days and `importance < 3`, multiply rank\n360:     by a decay factor (< 1).\n361:   - Recently-recalled memories get a freshness boost.\n362: - **Reporting:** `/openltm:health` summarises memories by decay bucket\n363:   (`fresh` / `aging` / `stale`) and surfaces top-5 staleness candidates.\n364: - **OQ3** (PRD §9): the exact function (linear / exponential / recall-driven) is open\n365:   and intended to be tuned with real recall logs.\n366: \n367: ### 5.6 Relationships\n368: \n369: ```mermaid\n\n(Showing lines 300-369 of 1075. Use offset=370 to continue.)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"`src/shared-db.ts`. WAL mode is enabled for read-during-write concurrency.\n\n### 5.1 Tables\n\n| Table | Purpose | Lifecycle |\n|-------|---------|-----------|\n| `memories` | Long-term, durable insights (decisions, gotchas, patterns, etc.). Global or project-scoped. | Permanent unless soft-deleted via `status` |\n| `context_items` | Short-term, per-project context. The 4 PRD-defined types: goal, decision, progress, gotcha. | Mixed: progress trimmed to last 20; goal replaced; decision/gotcha permanent |\n| `tags` | Tag dictionary (unique names). | Auto-created on use |\n| `memory_tags` | M:N join — memory ↔ tag. | Cascading on memory delete |\n| `memory_relations` | Knowledge graph edges between memories with typed relationship. | Cascading on memory delete |\n| `memories_fts` | FTS5 virtual table mirroring `memories.content`. | Maintained by triggers (insert/update/delete) |\n| `settings` | Key-value config for janitor / provider settings. | Manual or migration-managed |\n\n### 5.2 `memories` — key columns\n\n| Column | Purpose |\n|--------|---------|\n| `id` | Primary key, surrogate `INTEGER` |\n| `content` | The memory text. Subject to redaction on write. |","truncated":true,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/OpenLtm-main/docs/03-architecture.md","text":"`src/shared-db.ts`. WAL mode is enabled for read-during-write concurrency.\n\n### 5.1 Tables\n\n| Table | Purpose | Lifecycle |\n|-------|---------|-----------|\n| `memories` | Long-term, durable insights (decisions, gotchas, patterns, etc.). Global or project-scoped. | Permanent unless soft-deleted via `status` |\n| `context_items` | Short-term, per-project context. The 4 PRD-defined types: goal, decision, progress, gotcha. | Mixed: progress trimmed to last 20; goal replaced; decision/gotcha permanent |\n| `tags` | Tag dictionary (unique names). | Auto-created on use |\n| `memory_tags` | M:N join — memory ↔ tag. | Cascading on memory delete |\n| `memory_relations` | Knowledge graph edges between memories with typed relationship. | Cascading on memory delete |\n| `memories_fts` | FTS5 virtual table mirroring `memories.content`. | Maintained by triggers (insert/update/delete) |\n| `settings` | Key-value config for janitor / provider settings. | Manual or migration-managed |\n\n### 5.2 `memories` — key columns\n\n| Column | Purpose |\n|--------|---------|\n| `id` | Primary key, surrogate `INTEGER` |\n| `content` | The memory text. Subject to redaction on write. |\n| `category` | One of: `preference`, `architecture`, `gotcha`, `pattern`, `workflow`, `constraint` |\n| `importance` | 1–5; `5` opts a global memory into every-session injection |\n| `confidence` | 0.0–1.0; reserved for janitor / promotion logic |\n| `project_scope` | NULL = global; else project_name (joined with registry) |\n| `dedup_key` | UNIQUE; prevents repeated learns of the same fact |\n| `status` | `active` / `pending` / `deprecated` / `superseded` — soft-delete + supersession |\n| `embedding` | Float32 BLOB; semantic fallback vector. Stripped from MCP responses (would balloon to ~260 KB). |\n| `last_used_at`, `last_recalled_at`, `recall_count` | Decay inputs |\n| `superseded_by`, `superseded_at` | Pointer to the memory that replaced this one (audit trail) |\n| `workspace_id`, `agent_id` | T16 multi-agent metadata; indexed |\n\n### 5.3 `context_items` — key columns\n\n| Column | Purpose |\n|--------|---------|\n| `project_name` | Foreign-keyed by name to the registry |\n| `type` | `goal` / `decision` / `progress` / `gotcha` |\n| `content` | Free text |\n| `permanent` | 1 for decision/gotcha; 0 for goal/progress |\n| `memory_id` | Optional link back to a promoted global memory |\n| `status` | `active` / `pending_promotion` / `promoted` |\n\n### 5.4 FTS5 setup\n\n- `memories_fts` is a `content='memories'` external-content FTS5 virtual table.\n  Triggers (`memories_ai`, `memories_au`, `memories_ad`) keep the index in sync on\n  insert/update/delete.\n- Recall path: parameterised `MATCH` query against `memories_fts`, joined back to\n  `memories` for category/project/importance filters and decay scoring.\n- BM25 ranking is the default; the recall engine post-multiplies by importance and\n  decay factors before returning top-N.\n\n### 5.5 Decay model (current)\n\nThe current implementation applies decay at recall time, not as a stored score.\n\n- **Inputs:** `last_recalled_at`, `recall_count`, `importance`, `created_at`.\n- **Rule sketch:**\n  - If `importance == 5`, no decay.\n  - If memory has not been recalled in 90+ days and `importance < 3`, multiply rank\n    by a decay factor (< 1).\n  - Recently-recalled memories get a freshness boost.\n- **Reporting:** `/openltm:health` summarises memories by decay bucket\n  (`fresh` / `aging` / `stale`) and surfaces top-5 staleness candidates.\n- **OQ3** (PRD §9): the exact function (linear / exponential / recall-driven) is open\n  and intended to be tuned with real recall logs.\n\n### 5.6 Relationships\n\n```mermaid","lineStart":300,"lineEnd":369,"totalLines":1075,"truncated":true}},"title":"specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/OpenLtm-main/docs/03-architecture.md","time":{"start":1780925341845,"end":1780925341856}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_0765f137e9f02783016a26c39dae20819186674f2107bcfd48"}},"id":"prt_ea76c208b001itVwl3V7YyuRKb","sessionID":"ses_158954ac9ffePahLx5YfsvlJLH","messageID":"msg_ea76be466001gwQJbddIXqivKi"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1780925341893,"sessionID":"ses_158954ac9ffePahLx5YfsvlJLH","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_xBYCEUSjNH6TxRzM6iNrog1X","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/OpenLtm-main/docs/03-architecture.md","offset":511,"limit":38},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/OpenLtm-main/docs/03-architecture.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n511: ### ADR-004 — Memory decay model\n512: \n513: **Status:** Accepted (provisional). Function shape under experiment (PRD OQ3).\n514: \n515: **Context.** Without decay, recall results stagnate as the DB grows. PRD US-5 demands\n516: that low-importance, never-recalled memories fade. PRD G2 demands fresh, fast recall.\n517: \n518: **Decision.** Decay is computed at **recall time**, not stored. Inputs:\n519: `importance`, `last_recalled_at`, `recall_count`, `created_at`. Rules:\n520: \n521: 1. `importance == 5` → no decay (immortal memories).\n522: 2. Else if `(now - last_recalled_at) > 90 days` AND `importance < 3` → multiply\n523:    rank by a decay factor < 1.\n524: 3. Recently-recalled memories receive a freshness boost.\n525: \n526: The exact function form (linear, exponential, recall-driven) is configurable via\n527: the `settings` table and remains an open experiment.\n528: \n529: **Alternatives considered.**\n530: \n531: - **Stored decay score updated on a schedule.** Rejected for v1. Adds a janitor\n532:   cron, a write-amplification problem, and a stale-score hazard. Recompute-on-read\n533:   is cheap at single-user scale.\n534: - **Hard expiry / auto-delete.** Rejected. Violates the developer's expectation that\n535:   memories are durable. Decay should rerank, not destroy.\n536: - **No decay.** Rejected. Long-running projects would drown new recalls under old\n537:   ones (PRD §1.1 — \"stale knowledge decays gracefully\").\n538: \n539: **Consequences.**\n540: \n541: - (+) Zero write amplification; decay costs only at read time.\n542: - (+) Tunable without a migration — settings table holds parameters.\n543: - (–) Recall latency is sensitive to N (rows scanned). At scale this becomes a\n544:   problem (W4 in §7) — addressed in the magnificent architecture by precomputed\n545:   decay buckets.\n546: - (–) Importance must be set correctly by the user / EvaluateSession or the model\n547:   is gameable.\n548: \n\n(Showing lines 511-548 of 1075. Use offset=549 to continue.)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"### ADR-004 — Memory decay model\n\n**Status:** Accepted (provisional). Function shape under experiment (PRD OQ3).\n\n**Context.** Without decay, recall results stagnate as the DB grows. PRD US-5 demands\nthat low-importance, never-recalled memories fade. PRD G2 demands fresh, fast recall.\n\n**Decision.** Decay is computed at **recall time**, not stored. Inputs:\n`importance`, `last_recalled_at`, `recall_count`, `created_at`. Rules:\n\n1. `importance == 5` → no decay (immortal memories).\n2. Else if `(now - last_recalled_at) > 90 days` AND `importance < 3` → multiply\n   rank by a decay factor < 1.\n3. Recently-recalled memories receive a freshness boost.\n\nThe exact function form (linear, exponential, recall-driven) is configurable via\nthe `settings` table and remains an open experiment.\n\n**Alternatives considered.**\n","truncated":true,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/OpenLtm-main/docs/03-architecture.md","text":"### ADR-004 — Memory decay model\n\n**Status:** Accepted (provisional). Function shape under experiment (PRD OQ3).\n\n**Context.** Without decay, recall results stagnate as the DB grows. PRD US-5 demands\nthat low-importance, never-recalled memories fade. PRD G2 demands fresh, fast recall.\n\n**Decision.** Decay is computed at **recall time**, not stored. Inputs:\n`importance`, `last_recalled_at`, `recall_count`, `created_at`. Rules:\n\n1. `importance == 5` → no decay (immortal memories).\n2. Else if `(now - last_recalled_at) > 90 days` AND `importance < 3` → multiply\n   rank by a decay factor < 1.\n3. Recently-recalled memories receive a freshness boost.\n\nThe exact function form (linear, exponential, recall-driven) is configurable via\nthe `settings` table and remains an open experiment.\n\n**Alternatives considered.**\n\n- **Stored decay score updated on a schedule.** Rejected for v1. Adds a janitor\n  cron, a write-amplification problem, and a stale-score hazard. Recompute-on-read\n  is cheap at single-user scale.\n- **Hard expiry / auto-delete.** Rejected. Violates the developer's expectation that\n  memories are durable. Decay should rerank, not destroy.\n- **No decay.** Rejected. Long-running projects would drown new recalls under old\n  ones (PRD §1.1 — \"stale knowledge decays gracefully\").\n\n**Consequences.**\n\n- (+) Zero write amplification; decay costs only at read time.\n- (+) Tunable without a migration — settings table holds parameters.\n- (–) Recall latency is sensitive to N (rows scanned). At scale this becomes a\n  problem (W4 in §7) — addressed in the magnificent architecture by precomputed\n  decay buckets.\n- (–) Importance must be set correctly by the user / EvaluateSession or the model\n  is gameable.\n","lineStart":511,"lineEnd":548,"totalLines":1075,"truncated":true}},"title":"specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/OpenLtm-main/docs/03-architecture.md","time":{"start":1780925341858,"end":1780925341888}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_0765f137e9f02783016a26c39dae3481919a9599a404bcf6d0"}},"id":"prt_ea76c2097001XiloS7s8MoYNcU","sessionID":"ses_158954ac9ffePahLx5YfsvlJLH","messageID":"msg_ea76be466001gwQJbddIXqivKi"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1780925341895,"sessionID":"ses_158954ac9ffePahLx5YfsvlJLH","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_BUuIv2EOhQ6CvTdVooPBXghF","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/OpenLtm-main/docs/03-architecture.md","offset":669,"limit":62},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/OpenLtm-main/docs/03-architecture.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n669: **Direction.** Materialise a `decay_score` column maintained by a low-frequency\n670: janitor; use it in `ORDER BY`. Trade write amplification for read latency.\n671: \n672: ### W5 — No structured observability\n673: \n674: **Symptom.** Latency, recall hit rate, learn frequency — none are recorded. PRD §8\n675: metrics are aspirational without instrumentation.\n676: \n677: **Root cause.** No metrics surface. No event log table. `/openltm:health` reads\n678: counts but not timings.\n679: \n680: **Direction.** Add an `events` table (append-only): event_type, latency_ms,\n681: result_count, timestamp. Aggregate in `/openltm:health`.\n682: \n683: ### W6 — Cache vs. source-repo dual-write\n684: \n685: **Symptom.** \"I fixed it but it didn't take effect.\" See ADR-005.\n686: \n687: **Direction.** Add a `dev mode` flag that, when set, makes the cache directory a\n688: symlink to the source repo. Off by default for end users.\n689: \n690: ### W7 — MCP response size pressure\n691: \n692: **Symptom.** `embedding` BLOBs serialise as `{\"0\":59,\"1\":...}` JSON objects of\n693: ~260 KB each over MCP. The `compact`/`strip` formatter exists *because* of this.\n694: \n695: **Root cause.** MCP responses are JSON; embeddings are binary. The strip is a\n696: band-aid, not a fix.\n697: \n698: **Direction.** Move embeddings out of the `memories` table into a sibling\n699: `memory_embeddings(memory_id, vec BLOB)` table; MCP queries never join it.\n700: \n701: ### W8 — Coupling between hooks and DB schema\n702: \n703: **Symptom.** A schema change requires updating hooks, MCP server, and graph server\n704: together. Versioning is per-plugin, not per-component.\n705: \n706: **Direction.** Define a small data-access layer (DAO) in `src/dao/` with stable\n707: function signatures; everything else calls through it. Schema changes are then\n708: isolated to the DAO.\n709: \n710: ### W9 — No memory provenance\n711: \n712: **Symptom.** A recalled memory tells you *what* but not *where it came from*\n713: (which conversation turn, which commit, which file). G-J in the PRD calls this out.\n714: \n715: **Direction.** Add a `provenance` table or columns: source_type\n716: (`session` / `git-backfill` / `manual` / `evaluate`), source_ref (session id, SHA,\n717: file path).\n718: \n719: ### W10 — `EvaluateSession` policy is unclear\n720: \n721: **Symptom.** PRD OQ4: should EvaluateSession auto-write or always propose? Today's\n722: behaviour is implementation-defined and not surfaced to the user.\n723: \n724: **Direction.** Add a config flag (`evaluate.auto_promote`); default to \"propose,\n725: require user confirmation via a banner at next SessionStart\".\n726: \n727: ### W11 — No write audit trail\n728: \n729: **Symptom.** A memory is wrong; the user can `forget` it but cannot answer\n730: \"who/what wrote this in the first place?\".\n\n(Showing lines 669-730 of 1075. Use offset=731 to continue.)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"**Direction.** Materialise a `decay_score` column maintained by a low-frequency\njanitor; use it in `ORDER BY`. Trade write amplification for read latency.\n\n### W5 — No structured observability\n\n**Symptom.** Latency, recall hit rate, learn frequency — none are recorded. PRD §8\nmetrics are aspirational without instrumentation.\n\n**Root cause.** No metrics surface. No event log table. `/openltm:health` reads\ncounts but not timings.\n\n**Direction.** Add an `events` table (append-only): event_type, latency_ms,\nresult_count, timestamp. Aggregate in `/openltm:health`.\n\n### W6 — Cache vs. source-repo dual-write\n\n**Symptom.** \"I fixed it but it didn't take effect.\" See ADR-005.\n\n**Direction.** Add a `dev mode` flag that, when set, makes the cache directory a\nsymlink to the source repo. Off by default for end users.","truncated":true,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/OpenLtm-main/docs/03-architecture.md","text":"**Direction.** Materialise a `decay_score` column maintained by a low-frequency\njanitor; use it in `ORDER BY`. Trade write amplification for read latency.\n\n### W5 — No structured observability\n\n**Symptom.** Latency, recall hit rate, learn frequency — none are recorded. PRD §8\nmetrics are aspirational without instrumentation.\n\n**Root cause.** No metrics surface. No event log table. `/openltm:health` reads\ncounts but not timings.\n\n**Direction.** Add an `events` table (append-only): event_type, latency_ms,\nresult_count, timestamp. Aggregate in `/openltm:health`.\n\n### W6 — Cache vs. source-repo dual-write\n\n**Symptom.** \"I fixed it but it didn't take effect.\" See ADR-005.\n\n**Direction.** Add a `dev mode` flag that, when set, makes the cache directory a\nsymlink to the source repo. Off by default for end users.\n\n### W7 — MCP response size pressure\n\n**Symptom.** `embedding` BLOBs serialise as `{\"0\":59,\"1\":...}` JSON objects of\n~260 KB each over MCP. The `compact`/`strip` formatter exists *because* of this.\n\n**Root cause.** MCP responses are JSON; embeddings are binary. The strip is a\nband-aid, not a fix.\n\n**Direction.** Move embeddings out of the `memories` table into a sibling\n`memory_embeddings(memory_id, vec BLOB)` table; MCP queries never join it.\n\n### W8 — Coupling between hooks and DB schema\n\n**Symptom.** A schema change requires updating hooks, MCP server, and graph server\ntogether. Versioning is per-plugin, not per-component.\n\n**Direction.** Define a small data-access layer (DAO) in `src/dao/` with stable\nfunction signatures; everything else calls through it. Schema changes are then\nisolated to the DAO.\n\n### W9 — No memory provenance\n\n**Symptom.** A recalled memory tells you *what* but not *where it came from*\n(which conversation turn, which commit, which file). G-J in the PRD calls this out.\n\n**Direction.** Add a `provenance` table or columns: source_type\n(`session` / `git-backfill` / `manual` / `evaluate`), source_ref (session id, SHA,\nfile path).\n\n### W10 — `EvaluateSession` policy is unclear\n\n**Symptom.** PRD OQ4: should EvaluateSession auto-write or always propose? Today's\nbehaviour is implementation-defined and not surfaced to the user.\n\n**Direction.** Add a config flag (`evaluate.auto_promote`); default to \"propose,\nrequire user confirmation via a banner at next SessionStart\".\n\n### W11 — No write audit trail\n\n**Symptom.** A memory is wrong; the user can `forget` it but cannot answer\n\"who/what wrote this in the first place?\".","lineStart":669,"lineEnd":730,"totalLines":1075,"truncated":true}},"title":"specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/OpenLtm-main/docs/03-architecture.md","time":{"start":1780925341868,"end":1780925341890}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_0765f137e9f02783016a26c39dae4081918ed89c85187b0d64"}},"id":"prt_ea76c20a30014f92zFp9xgU3C3","sessionID":"ses_158954ac9ffePahLx5YfsvlJLH","messageID":"msg_ea76be466001gwQJbddIXqivKi"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1780925341895,"sessionID":"ses_158954ac9ffePahLx5YfsvlJLH","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_aYu6ynNVolhspbftompc3dw3","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/OpenLtm-main/docs/03-architecture.md","offset":850,"limit":45},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/OpenLtm-main/docs/03-architecture.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n850: **Opt-in.** Default off. Configurable via `/openltm:admin sync setup`.\n851: \n852: ### 8.5 C3 — Team memory bundles (signed export/import)\n853: \n854: A bundle is a JSON file: schema-version + array of memories + array of relations,\n855: signed with the exporter's keypair. Importer verifies signature, then enters a\n856: **review flow** (not auto-merge): each incoming memory is staged with status\n857: `pending`, surfaced at next SessionStart, accepted/rejected one by one.\n858: \n859: Bundles target the team-lead persona Tara without crossing into multi-tenant\n860: territory. Memory remains per-developer; bundles are a transport.\n861: \n862: ### 8.6 C4 — Conflict detection on learn\n863: \n864: When `learn` is called, the Learn Engine first runs a similarity check against\n865: existing memories. If `(similarity > 0.85) AND (polarity_opposite OR same_dedup_topic)`,\n866: the new memory is staged `pending` with a link to the conflicting memory. The user\n867: is asked at next SessionStart: *forget*, *supersede*, or *coexist*.\n868: \n869: This makes the LTM **self-curating** (PRD §1.1).\n870: \n871: ### 8.7 C5 — Provenance chain\n872: \n873: Every memory gets a `provenance` row chain:\n874: \n875: ```mermaid\n876: flowchart LR\n877:   M[Memory m_42] -- provenance --> P1[source: session sess_abc, turn 7]\n878:   M -- provenance --> P2[source: git-backfill, sha def123]\n879:   M -- provenance --> P3[source: evaluate-session, score 0.92]\n880:   M -- provenance --> P4[source: user-promotion, importance bumped 3 to 5]\n881: ```\n882: \n883: Recall results carry provenance; the explainer (C8) surfaces it inline.\n884: \n885: ### 8.8 C6 — Memory compression / rollups\n886: \n887: When memory count for a project exceeds a threshold (config), the janitor clusters\n888: related memories (by tag overlap + embedding similarity) and proposes a *rollup*:\n889: one new summary memory linked to N source memories via `supersedes` edges. Sources\n890: move to `status='deprecated'` but are retained for time-travel (C9).\n891: \n892: ### 8.9 C7 — Cross-plugin memory contract\n893: \n894: Today the LTM is a silo. Other plugins (`task-tracker`, `code-review`,\n\n(Showing lines 850-894 of 1075. Use offset=895 to continue.)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"**Opt-in.** Default off. Configurable via `/openltm:admin sync setup`.\n\n### 8.5 C3 — Team memory bundles (signed export/import)\n\nA bundle is a JSON file: schema-version + array of memories + array of relations,\nsigned with the exporter's keypair. Importer verifies signature, then enters a\n**review flow** (not auto-merge): each incoming memory is staged with status\n`pending`, surfaced at next SessionStart, accepted/rejected one by one.\n\nBundles target the team-lead persona Tara without crossing into multi-tenant\nterritory. Memory remains per-developer; bundles are a transport.\n\n### 8.6 C4 — Conflict detection on learn\n\nWhen `learn` is called, the Learn Engine first runs a similarity check against\nexisting memories. If `(similarity > 0.85) AND (polarity_opposite OR same_dedup_topic)`,\nthe new memory is staged `pending` with a link to the conflicting memory. The user\nis asked at next SessionStart: *forget*, *supersede*, or *coexist*.\n\nThis makes the LTM **self-curating** (PRD §1.1).","truncated":true,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/OpenLtm-main/docs/03-architecture.md","text":"**Opt-in.** Default off. Configurable via `/openltm:admin sync setup`.\n\n### 8.5 C3 — Team memory bundles (signed export/import)\n\nA bundle is a JSON file: schema-version + array of memories + array of relations,\nsigned with the exporter's keypair. Importer verifies signature, then enters a\n**review flow** (not auto-merge): each incoming memory is staged with status\n`pending`, surfaced at next SessionStart, accepted/rejected one by one.\n\nBundles target the team-lead persona Tara without crossing into multi-tenant\nterritory. Memory remains per-developer; bundles are a transport.\n\n### 8.6 C4 — Conflict detection on learn\n\nWhen `learn` is called, the Learn Engine first runs a similarity check against\nexisting memories. If `(similarity > 0.85) AND (polarity_opposite OR same_dedup_topic)`,\nthe new memory is staged `pending` with a link to the conflicting memory. The user\nis asked at next SessionStart: *forget*, *supersede*, or *coexist*.\n\nThis makes the LTM **self-curating** (PRD §1.1).\n\n### 8.7 C5 — Provenance chain\n\nEvery memory gets a `provenance` row chain:\n\n```mermaid\nflowchart LR\n  M[Memory m_42] -- provenance --> P1[source: session sess_abc, turn 7]\n  M -- provenance --> P2[source: git-backfill, sha def123]\n  M -- provenance --> P3[source: evaluate-session, score 0.92]\n  M -- provenance --> P4[source: user-promotion, importance bumped 3 to 5]\n```\n\nRecall results carry provenance; the explainer (C8) surfaces it inline.\n\n### 8.8 C6 — Memory compression / rollups\n\nWhen memory count for a project exceeds a threshold (config), the janitor clusters\nrelated memories (by tag overlap + embedding similarity) and proposes a *rollup*:\none new summary memory linked to N source memories via `supersedes` edges. Sources\nmove to `status='deprecated'` but are retained for time-travel (C9).\n\n### 8.9 C7 — Cross-plugin memory contract\n\nToday the LTM is a silo. Other plugins (`task-tracker`, `code-review`,","lineStart":850,"lineEnd":894,"totalLines":1075,"truncated":true}},"title":"specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/OpenLtm-main/docs/03-architecture.md","time":{"start":1780925341872,"end":1780925341892}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_0765f137e9f02783016a26c39dae4c8191a9c29b3c8cbb5a27"}},"id":"prt_ea76c20ae001gjRP5fNrcOML05","sessionID":"ses_158954ac9ffePahLx5YfsvlJLH","messageID":"msg_ea76be466001gwQJbddIXqivKi"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1780925341901,"sessionID":"ses_158954ac9ffePahLx5YfsvlJLH","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_KJbDVU1WNTMxd7jLPoyKJrKS","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/OpenLtm-main/docs/internal/DB-SPEC.md","offset":1,"limit":260},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/OpenLtm-main/docs/internal/DB-SPEC.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: # DB-SPEC — OpenLTM Plugin Database Specification\n2: \n3: **Version:** 1.0\n4: **Owner:** database-admin (dev-team)\n5: **Status:** Current schema spec against plugin v2.8.0\n6: **Last updated:** 2026-06-08\n7: **Companion documents:** `docs/03-architecture.md`, `docs/internal/PRD.md`, `docs/internal/ROADMAP.md`\n8: \n9: This document is the authoritative reference for the LTM plugin data tier. It covers\n10: the current schema (annotated), index strategy, FTS5 configuration, the decay model,\n11: the migration system, concurrency safety, the full \"magnificent\" DDL target, performance\n12: at scale, and the per-phase schema evolution plan aligned to `ROADMAP.md §3`.\n13: \n14: `ROADMAP.md §6` (Schema Evolution) references this document. Once sections land, that\n15: doc's phase tables should be updated to reference the exact migration filenames defined\n16: in §9 below.\n17: \n18: ---\n19: \n20: ## Table of Contents\n21: \n22: 1. Current Schema — Annotated\n23: 2. Index Strategy Analysis\n24: 3. FTS5 Configuration and Recall\n25: 4. Memory Decay Model\n26: 5. Migration System\n27: 6. Concurrency and Safety\n28: 7. The Magnificent Schema — Full DDL\n29: 8. Performance at Scale\n30: 9. Migration Path — Schema Evolution\n31: \n32: ---\n33: \n34: ## 1. Current Schema — Annotated\n35: \n36: The entire data store is one SQLite file: `${CLAUDE_PLUGIN_DATA}/OpenLtm-openltm/openltm.db`.\n37: Accessed exclusively through `src/shared-db.ts:getDb()`. WAL mode, foreign keys on,\n38: busy_timeout 5 000 ms set on every connection.\n39: \n40: Schema source of truth: `src/schema.sql` (initial tables + FTS + triggers).\n41: Migration overlay: `src/shared-db.ts:runMigrations()` (idempotent column adds).\n42: \n43: ### 1.1 `memories`\n44: \n45: The core table. Every durable insight the plugin has stored, whether from `learn`,\n46: GitLearn backfill, EvaluateSession, or bundle import.\n47: \n48: ```sql\n49: CREATE TABLE memories (\n50:   id                INTEGER PRIMARY KEY AUTOINCREMENT,\n51:   -- Content and classification\n52:   content           TEXT    NOT NULL,\n53:   category          TEXT    NOT NULL CHECK(category IN (\n54:                       'preference','architecture','gotcha','pattern','workflow','constraint')),\n55:   importance        INTEGER NOT NULL DEFAULT 3 CHECK(importance BETWEEN 1 AND 5),\n56:   confidence        REAL    NOT NULL DEFAULT 1.0 CHECK(confidence BETWEEN 0.0 AND 1.0),\n57:   source            TEXT,                       -- free-text provenance hint (pre-Phase 2)\n58:   project_scope     TEXT,                       -- NULL = global; else project_name\n59:   dedup_key         TEXT    UNIQUE,             -- normalised hash; prevents repeat learns\n60: \n61:   -- Timestamps\n62:   created_at        TEXT    NOT NULL DEFAULT (datetime('now')),\n63:   last_confirmed_at TEXT    NOT NULL DEFAULT (datetime('now')),\n64:   confirm_count     INTEGER NOT NULL DEFAULT 1,\n65: \n66:   -- Lifecycle (Phase 2 migration, now in schema.sql)\n67:   status            TEXT    NOT NULL DEFAULT 'active' CHECK(status IN (\n68:                       'active','pending','deprecated','superseded')),\n69: \n70:   -- Embedding (Phase 1 split candidate)\n71:   embedding         BLOB,                       -- float32 vector; stripped from MCP responses\n72: \n73:   -- Recall telemetry (Phase 3 migration)\n74:   last_used_at      TEXT    NOT NULL DEFAULT (datetime('now')),\n75:   first_recalled_at TEXT,\n76:   last_recalled_at  TEXT,\n77:   recall_count      INTEGER NOT NULL DEFAULT 0,\n78: \n79:   -- Supersession chain (Phase 2 migration)\n80:   superseded_by     INTEGER REFERENCES memories(id) ON DELETE SET NULL,\n81:   superseded_at     TEXT,\n82: \n83:   -- Multi-agent metadata (T16 migration)\n84:   workspace_id      TEXT,\n85:   agent_id          TEXT\n86: );\n87: ```\n88: \n89: **Column rationale**\n90: \n91: | Column | Rationale |\n92: |--------|-----------|\n93: | `category` | Six-value enum enforced by CHECK; drives the SessionStart injection filter (importance-5 + category) |\n94: | `importance` | 1–5 ordinal; 5 = immortal (no decay); drives every-session injection threshold |\n95: | `confidence` | Reserved for EvaluateSession and the future janitor's auto-demotion logic; not yet surfaced to users |\n96: | `dedup_key` | UNIQUE; prevents a session that keeps re-learning the same fact from polluting the table; computed by the Learn Engine as a normalised content hash |\n97: | `project_scope` | NULL = global (injected in all sessions); non-null = scoped to one project (joined against the `registry.json` project_name) |\n98: | `status` | Soft-delete / workflow state; recall queries filter to `status = 'active'` |\n99: | `embedding` | Stored as a raw BLOB (float32 array). At 1536 dimensions = ~6 KB per row; serialised to JSON over MCP it becomes ~260 KB. The compact formatter strips it before every MCP response. Phase 1 moves it to a separate table. |\n100: | `last_used_at`, `last_recalled_at`, `recall_count` | Inputs to the recall-time decay calculation. `last_used_at` covers both learn-time touch and recall-time touch; `last_recalled_at` covers recall only. |\n101: | `superseded_by` | Self-referential FK; forms the supersession chain for time-travel (Phase 7) |\n102: | `workspace_id`, `agent_id` | Multi-agent isolation (ROADMAP Phase 5 / T16); both indexed |\n103: \n104: ### 1.2 `context_items`\n105: \n106: Per-project short-term context. Replaces the four Markdown files that existed before v1.0.\n107: \n108: ```sql\n109: CREATE TABLE context_items (\n110:   id           INTEGER PRIMARY KEY AUTOINCREMENT,\n111:   project_name TEXT    NOT NULL,\n112:   type         TEXT    NOT NULL CHECK(type IN ('goal','decision','progress','gotcha')),\n113:   content      TEXT    NOT NULL,\n114:   session_id   TEXT,                          -- for progress dedup across same session\n115:   permanent    INTEGER NOT NULL DEFAULT 0,    -- 1 = never auto-trim (decision, gotcha)\n116:   memory_id    INTEGER REFERENCES memories(id) ON DELETE SET NULL,  -- Phase 1 migration\n117:   status       TEXT    NOT NULL DEFAULT 'active' CHECK(status IN (\n118:                  'active','pending_promotion','promoted')),          -- Phase 2 migration\n119:   created_at   TEXT    NOT NULL DEFAULT (datetime('now')),\n120:   workspace_id TEXT,                          -- T16 multi-agent isolation\n121:   agent_id     TEXT                           -- T16\n122: );\n123: ```\n124: \n125: **Lifecycle by type**\n126: \n127: | Type | `permanent` | Trim rule |\n128: |------|-------------|-----------|\n129: | `goal` | 0 | Replaced when a new goal is written |\n130: | `decision` | 1 | Never auto-trimmed; manual removal only |\n131: | `progress` | 0 | Trimmed to last 20 per project by UpdateContext hook |\n132: | `gotcha` | 1 | Never auto-trimmed |\n133: \n134: **`status` flow**\n135: \n136: ```\n137: active -> pending_promotion -> promoted\n138:                            (memory_id set once promoted to memories table)\n139: ```\n140: \n141: ### 1.3 `tags` and `memory_tags`\n142: \n143: Many-to-many tagging for memories. Tags are auto-created on use; the dictionary is normalised to avoid duplication.\n144: \n145: ```sql\n146: CREATE TABLE tags (\n147:   id   INTEGER PRIMARY KEY AUTOINCREMENT,\n148:   name TEXT    NOT NULL UNIQUE\n149: );\n150: \n151: CREATE TABLE memory_tags (\n152:   memory_id INTEGER NOT NULL REFERENCES memories(id) ON DELETE CASCADE,\n153:   tag_id    INTEGER NOT NULL REFERENCES tags(id)     ON DELETE CASCADE,\n154:   PRIMARY KEY (memory_id, tag_id)\n155: );\n156: ```\n157: \n158: No additional indexes needed: the composite PK covers `(memory_id, tag_id)` lookup; `ON DELETE CASCADE` keeps the join table clean without a separate job.\n159: \n160: ### 1.4 `memory_relations`\n161: \n162: Knowledge graph edges. Six typed relationship directions. Used by `relate` and traversed by `graph` (BFS via `src/graph.ts`).\n163: \n164: ```sql\n165: CREATE TABLE memory_relations (\n166:   id               INTEGER PRIMARY KEY AUTOINCREMENT,\n167:   source_memory_id INTEGER NOT NULL REFERENCES memories(id) ON DELETE CASCADE,\n168:   target_memory_id INTEGER NOT NULL REFERENCES memories(id) ON DELETE CASCADE,\n169:   relationship_type TEXT NOT NULL CHECK(relationship_type IN (\n170:                       'supports','contradicts','refines','depends_on','related_to','supersedes')),\n171:   created_at TEXT NOT NULL DEFAULT (datetime('now')),\n172:   UNIQUE(source_memory_id, target_memory_id, relationship_type)\n173: );\n174: ```\n175: \n176: The UNIQUE constraint on the triple prevents duplicate edges for the same relationship type. Cascade on both FKs means deleting a memory automatically prunes all edges.\n177: \n178: ### 1.5 `memories_fts`\n179: \n180: FTS5 external-content virtual table. Shadows `memories.content`. Maintained by three triggers.\n181: \n182: ```sql\n183: CREATE VIRTUAL TABLE memories_fts USING fts5(\n184:   content,\n185:   content='memories',\n186:   content_rowid='id'\n187: );\n188: \n189: CREATE TRIGGER memories_ai AFTER INSERT ON memories BEGIN\n190:   INSERT INTO memories_fts(rowid, content) VALUES (new.id, new.content);\n191: END;\n192: CREATE TRIGGER memories_ad AFTER DELETE ON memories BEGIN\n193:   INSERT INTO memories_fts(memories_fts, rowid, content) VALUES ('delete', old.id, old.content);\n194: END;\n195: CREATE TRIGGER memories_au AFTER UPDATE ON memories BEGIN\n196:   INSERT INTO memories_fts(memories_fts, rowid, content) VALUES ('delete', old.id, old.content);\n197:   INSERT INTO memories_fts(rowid, content) VALUES (new.id, new.content);\n198: END;\n199: ```\n200: \n201: See §3 for full FTS5 configuration analysis.\n202: \n203: ### 1.6 `settings`\n204: \n205: Key-value store for janitor configuration, provider selection, decay parameters, and\n206: feature flags.\n207: \n208: ```sql\n209: CREATE TABLE settings (\n210:   key        TEXT PRIMARY KEY,\n211:   value      TEXT NOT NULL,\n212:   updated_at TEXT NOT NULL DEFAULT (datetime('now'))\n213: );\n214: ```\n215: \n216: Known keys (as of v1.4.20):\n217: \n218: | Key | Expected type | Purpose |\n219: |-----|--------------|---------|\n220: | `decay.half_life_days` | integer | Days before a non-recalled memory halves its rank boost |\n221: | `decay.immortal_importance` | integer | Importance threshold above which decay is skipped |\n222: | `embedding.provider` | string | `null` / `local-hash` / `claude-tool` / `onnx` |\n223: | `janitor.enabled` | boolean | Master switch for Phase 4 janitor |\n224: | `janitor.last_run_at` | ISO8601 | Timestamp of last janitor pass |\n225: \n226: ---\n227: \n228: ## 2. Index Strategy Analysis\n229: \n230: ### 2.1 Existing indexes\n231: \n232: | Index | Table | Columns | Rationale |\n233: |-------|-------|---------|-----------|\n234: | `idx_ctx_project` | `context_items` | `project_name` | SessionStart: `WHERE project_name = ?` |\n235: | `idx_ctx_type` | `context_items` | `(project_name, type)` | SessionStart per-type fetch; composite covers both equality predicates |\n236: | `idx_memories_category` | `memories` | `category` | Filter by category in recall and health commands |\n237: | `idx_memories_project` | `memories` | `project_scope` | Scoped recall: `WHERE project_scope = ? OR project_scope IS NULL` |\n238: | `idx_memories_importance` | `memories` | `importance DESC` | SessionStart global injection (`importance = 5`); importance ordering |\n239: | `idx_memories_confidence` | `memories` | `confidence DESC` | Future janitor demotion; currently unused on hot path |\n240: | `idx_memories_status` | `memories` | `status` | All read paths filter `status = 'active'` |\n241: | `idx_memories_last_used` | `memories` | `last_used_at` | Decay input; janitor staleness scan |\n242: | `idx_memories_superseded` | `memories` | `superseded_by` | Supersession chain traversal |\n243: | `idx_memories_recall_count` | `memories` | `recall_count DESC` | Health reporting: top-recalled memories |\n244: | `idx_memories_workspace` | `memories` | `workspace_id` | T16 multi-agent isolation |\n245: | `idx_memories_agent` | `memories` | `agent_id` | T16 |\n246: | `idx_relations_source` | `memory_relations` | `source_memory_id` | BFS forward traversal |\n247: | `idx_relations_target` | `memory_relations` | `target_memory_id` | BFS reverse traversal |\n248: \n249: ### 2.2 Hot-path scan analysis\n250: \n251: **Hot path 1: `recall` (most frequent)**\n252: \n253: Query skeleton:\n254: ```sql\n255: SELECT m.id, m.content, m.importance, m.last_recalled_at, m.recall_count\n256: FROM memories_fts\n257: JOIN memories m ON memories_fts.rowid = m.id\n258: WHERE memories_fts MATCH ?\n259:   AND m.status = 'active'\n260:   AND (m.project_scope = ? OR m.project_scope IS NULL)\n\n(Showing lines 1-260 of 1105. Use offset=261 to continue.)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"# DB-SPEC — OpenLTM Plugin Database Specification\n\n**Version:** 1.0\n**Owner:** database-admin (dev-team)\n**Status:** Current schema spec against plugin v2.8.0\n**Last updated:** 2026-06-08\n**Companion documents:** `docs/03-architecture.md`, `docs/internal/PRD.md`, `docs/internal/ROADMAP.md`\n\nThis document is the authoritative reference for the LTM plugin data tier. It covers\nthe current schema (annotated), index strategy, FTS5 configuration, the decay model,\nthe migration system, concurrency safety, the full \"magnificent\" DDL target, performance\nat scale, and the per-phase schema evolution plan aligned to `ROADMAP.md §3`.\n\n`ROADMAP.md §6` (Schema Evolution) references this document. Once sections land, that\ndoc's phase tables should be updated to reference the exact migration filenames defined\nin §9 below.\n\n---\n\n## Table of Contents","truncated":true,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/OpenLtm-main/docs/internal/DB-SPEC.md","text":"# DB-SPEC — OpenLTM Plugin Database Specification\n\n**Version:** 1.0\n**Owner:** database-admin (dev-team)\n**Status:** Current schema spec against plugin v2.8.0\n**Last updated:** 2026-06-08\n**Companion documents:** `docs/03-architecture.md`, `docs/internal/PRD.md`, `docs/internal/ROADMAP.md`\n\nThis document is the authoritative reference for the LTM plugin data tier. It covers\nthe current schema (annotated), index strategy, FTS5 configuration, the decay model,\nthe migration system, concurrency safety, the full \"magnificent\" DDL target, performance\nat scale, and the per-phase schema evolution plan aligned to `ROADMAP.md §3`.\n\n`ROADMAP.md §6` (Schema Evolution) references this document. Once sections land, that\ndoc's phase tables should be updated to reference the exact migration filenames defined\nin §9 below.\n\n---\n\n## Table of Contents\n\n1. Current Schema — Annotated\n2. Index Strategy Analysis\n3. FTS5 Configuration and Recall\n4. Memory Decay Model\n5. Migration System\n6. Concurrency and Safety\n7. The Magnificent Schema — Full DDL\n8. Performance at Scale\n9. Migration Path — Schema Evolution\n\n---\n\n## 1. Current Schema — Annotated\n\nThe entire data store is one SQLite file: `${CLAUDE_PLUGIN_DATA}/OpenLtm-openltm/openltm.db`.\nAccessed exclusively through `src/shared-db.ts:getDb()`. WAL mode, foreign keys on,\nbusy_timeout 5 000 ms set on every connection.\n\nSchema source of truth: `src/schema.sql` (initial tables + FTS + triggers).\nMigration overlay: `src/shared-db.ts:runMigrations()` (idempotent column adds).\n\n### 1.1 `memories`\n\nThe core table. Every durable insight the plugin has stored, whether from `learn`,\nGitLearn backfill, EvaluateSession, or bundle import.\n\n```sql\nCREATE TABLE memories (\n  id                INTEGER PRIMARY KEY AUTOINCREMENT,\n  -- Content and classification\n  content           TEXT    NOT NULL,\n  category          TEXT    NOT NULL CHECK(category IN (\n                      'preference','architecture','gotcha','pattern','workflow','constraint')),\n  importance        INTEGER NOT NULL DEFAULT 3 CHECK(importance BETWEEN 1 AND 5),\n  confidence        REAL    NOT NULL DEFAULT 1.0 CHECK(confidence BETWEEN 0.0 AND 1.0),\n  source            TEXT,                       -- free-text provenance hint (pre-Phase 2)\n  project_scope     TEXT,                       -- NULL = global; else project_name\n  dedup_key         TEXT    UNIQUE,             -- normalised hash; prevents repeat learns\n\n  -- Timestamps\n  created_at        TEXT    NOT NULL DEFAULT (datetime('now')),\n  last_confirmed_at TEXT    NOT NULL DEFAULT (datetime('now')),\n  confirm_count     INTEGER NOT NULL DEFAULT 1,\n\n  -- Lifecycle (Phase 2 migration, now in schema.sql)\n  status            TEXT    NOT NULL DEFAULT 'active' CHECK(status IN (\n                      'active','pending','deprecated','superseded')),\n\n  -- Embedding (Phase 1 split candidate)\n  embedding         BLOB,                       -- float32 vector; stripped from MCP responses\n\n  -- Recall telemetry (Phase 3 migration)\n  last_used_at      TEXT    NOT NULL DEFAULT (datetime('now')),\n  first_recalled_at TEXT,\n  last_recalled_at  TEXT,\n  recall_count      INTEGER NOT NULL DEFAULT 0,\n\n  -- Supersession chain (Phase 2 migration)\n  superseded_by     INTEGER REFERENCES memories(id) ON DELETE SET NULL,\n  superseded_at     TEXT,\n\n  -- Multi-agent metadata (T16 migration)\n  workspace_id      TEXT,\n  agent_id          TEXT\n);\n```\n\n**Column rationale**\n\n| Column | Rationale |\n|--------|-----------|\n| `category` | Six-value enum enforced by CHECK; drives the SessionStart injection filter (importance-5 + category) |\n| `importance` | 1–5 ordinal; 5 = immortal (no decay); drives every-session injection threshold |\n| `confidence` | Reserved for EvaluateSession and the future janitor's auto-demotion logic; not yet surfaced to users |\n| `dedup_key` | UNIQUE; prevents a session that keeps re-learning the same fact from polluting the table; computed by the Learn Engine as a normalised content hash |\n| `project_scope` | NULL = global (injected in all sessions); non-null = scoped to one project (joined against the `registry.json` project_name) |\n| `status` | Soft-delete / workflow state; recall queries filter to `status = 'active'` |\n| `embedding` | Stored as a raw BLOB (float32 array). At 1536 dimensions = ~6 KB per row; serialised to JSON over MCP it becomes ~260 KB. The compact formatter strips it before every MCP response. Phase 1 moves it to a separate table. |\n| `last_used_at`, `last_recalled_at`, `recall_count` | Inputs to the recall-time decay calculation. `last_used_at` covers both learn-time touch and recall-time touch; `last_recalled_at` covers recall only. |\n| `superseded_by` | Self-referential FK; forms the supersession chain for time-travel (Phase 7) |\n| `workspace_id`, `agent_id` | Multi-agent isolation (ROADMAP Phase 5 / T16); both indexed |\n\n### 1.2 `context_items`\n\nPer-project short-term context. Replaces the four Markdown files that existed before v1.0.\n\n```sql\nCREATE TABLE context_items (\n  id           INTEGER PRIMARY KEY AUTOINCREMENT,\n  project_name TEXT    NOT NULL,\n  type         TEXT    NOT NULL CHECK(type IN ('goal','decision','progress','gotcha')),\n  content      TEXT    NOT NULL,\n  session_id   TEXT,                          -- for progress dedup across same session\n  permanent    INTEGER NOT NULL DEFAULT 0,    -- 1 = never auto-trim (decision, gotcha)\n  memory_id    INTEGER REFERENCES memories(id) ON DELETE SET NULL,  -- Phase 1 migration\n  status       TEXT    NOT NULL DEFAULT 'active' CHECK(status IN (\n                 'active','pending_promotion','promoted')),          -- Phase 2 migration\n  created_at   TEXT    NOT NULL DEFAULT (datetime('now')),\n  workspace_id TEXT,                          -- T16 multi-agent isolation\n  agent_id     TEXT                           -- T16\n);\n```\n\n**Lifecycle by type**\n\n| Type | `permanent` | Trim rule |\n|------|-------------|-----------|\n| `goal` | 0 | Replaced when a new goal is written |\n| `decision` | 1 | Never auto-trimmed; manual removal only |\n| `progress` | 0 | Trimmed to last 20 per project by UpdateContext hook |\n| `gotcha` | 1 | Never auto-trimmed |\n\n**`status` flow**\n\n```\nactive -> pending_promotion -> promoted\n                           (memory_id set once promoted to memories table)\n```\n\n### 1.3 `tags` and `memory_tags`\n\nMany-to-many tagging for memories. Tags are auto-created on use; the dictionary is normalised to avoid duplication.\n\n```sql\nCREATE TABLE tags (\n  id   INTEGER PRIMARY KEY AUTOINCREMENT,\n  name TEXT    NOT NULL UNIQUE\n);\n\nCREATE TABLE memory_tags (\n  memory_id INTEGER NOT NULL REFERENCES memories(id) ON DELETE CASCADE,\n  tag_id    INTEGER NOT NULL REFERENCES tags(id)     ON DELETE CASCADE,\n  PRIMARY KEY (memory_id, tag_id)\n);\n```\n\nNo additional indexes needed: the composite PK covers `(memory_id, tag_id)` lookup; `ON DELETE CASCADE` keeps the join table clean without a separate job.\n\n### 1.4 `memory_relations`\n\nKnowledge graph edges. Six typed relationship directions. Used by `relate` and traversed by `graph` (BFS via `src/graph.ts`).\n\n```sql\nCREATE TABLE memory_relations (\n  id               INTEGER PRIMARY KEY AUTOINCREMENT,\n  source_memory_id INTEGER NOT NULL REFERENCES memories(id) ON DELETE CASCADE,\n  target_memory_id INTEGER NOT NULL REFERENCES memories(id) ON DELETE CASCADE,\n  relationship_type TEXT NOT NULL CHECK(relationship_type IN (\n                      'supports','contradicts','refines','depends_on','related_to','supersedes')),\n  created_at TEXT NOT NULL DEFAULT (datetime('now')),\n  UNIQUE(source_memory_id, target_memory_id, relationship_type)\n);\n```\n\nThe UNIQUE constraint on the triple prevents duplicate edges for the same relationship type. Cascade on both FKs means deleting a memory automatically prunes all edges.\n\n### 1.5 `memories_fts`\n\nFTS5 external-content virtual table. Shadows `memories.content`. Maintained by three triggers.\n\n```sql\nCREATE VIRTUAL TABLE memories_fts USING fts5(\n  content,\n  content='memories',\n  content_rowid='id'\n);\n\nCREATE TRIGGER memories_ai AFTER INSERT ON memories BEGIN\n  INSERT INTO memories_fts(rowid, content) VALUES (new.id, new.content);\nEND;\nCREATE TRIGGER memories_ad AFTER DELETE ON memories BEGIN\n  INSERT INTO memories_fts(memories_fts, rowid, content) VALUES ('delete', old.id, old.content);\nEND;\nCREATE TRIGGER memories_au AFTER UPDATE ON memories BEGIN\n  INSERT INTO memories_fts(memories_fts, rowid, content) VALUES ('delete', old.id, old.content);\n  INSERT INTO memories_fts(rowid, content) VALUES (new.id, new.content);\nEND;\n```\n\nSee §3 for full FTS5 configuration analysis.\n\n### 1.6 `settings`\n\nKey-value store for janitor configuration, provider selection, decay parameters, and\nfeature flags.\n\n```sql\nCREATE TABLE settings (\n  key        TEXT PRIMARY KEY,\n  value      TEXT NOT NULL,\n  updated_at TEXT NOT NULL DEFAULT (datetime('now'))\n);\n```\n\nKnown keys (as of v1.4.20):\n\n| Key | Expected type | Purpose |\n|-----|--------------|---------|\n| `decay.half_life_days` | integer | Days before a non-recalled memory halves its rank boost |\n| `decay.immortal_importance` | integer | Importance threshold above which decay is skipped |\n| `embedding.provider` | string | `null` / `local-hash` / `claude-tool` / `onnx` |\n| `janitor.enabled` | boolean | Master switch for Phase 4 janitor |\n| `janitor.last_run_at` | ISO8601 | Timestamp of last janitor pass |\n\n---\n\n## 2. Index Strategy Analysis\n\n### 2.1 Existing indexes\n\n| Index | Table | Columns | Rationale |\n|-------|-------|---------|-----------|\n| `idx_ctx_project` | `context_items` | `project_name` | SessionStart: `WHERE project_name = ?` |\n| `idx_ctx_type` | `context_items` | `(project_name, type)` | SessionStart per-type fetch; composite covers both equality predicates |\n| `idx_memories_category` | `memories` | `category` | Filter by category in recall and health commands |\n| `idx_memories_project` | `memories` | `project_scope` | Scoped recall: `WHERE project_scope = ? OR project_scope IS NULL` |\n| `idx_memories_importance` | `memories` | `importance DESC` | SessionStart global injection (`importance = 5`); importance ordering |\n| `idx_memories_confidence` | `memories` | `confidence DESC` | Future janitor demotion; currently unused on hot path |\n| `idx_memories_status` | `memories` | `status` | All read paths filter `status = 'active'` |\n| `idx_memories_last_used` | `memories` | `last_used_at` | Decay input; janitor staleness scan |\n| `idx_memories_superseded` | `memories` | `superseded_by` | Supersession chain traversal |\n| `idx_memories_recall_count` | `memories` | `recall_count DESC` | Health reporting: top-recalled memories |\n| `idx_memories_workspace` | `memories` | `workspace_id` | T16 multi-agent isolation |\n| `idx_memories_agent` | `memories` | `agent_id` | T16 |\n| `idx_relations_source` | `memory_relations` | `source_memory_id` | BFS forward traversal |\n| `idx_relations_target` | `memory_relations` | `target_memory_id` | BFS reverse traversal |\n\n### 2.2 Hot-path scan analysis\n\n**Hot path 1: `recall` (most frequent)**\n\nQuery skeleton:\n```sql\nSELECT m.id, m.content, m.importance, m.last_recalled_at, m.recall_count\nFROM memories_fts\nJOIN memories m ON memories_fts.rowid = m.id\nWHERE memories_fts MATCH ?\n  AND m.status = 'active'\n  AND (m.project_scope = ? OR m.project_scope IS NULL)","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":260,"totalLines":1105,"truncated":true}},"title":"specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/OpenLtm-main/docs/internal/DB-SPEC.md","time":{"start":1780925341875,"end":1780925341899}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_0765f137e9f02783016a26c39daea48191a5db713ef2dd879e"}},"id":"prt_ea76c20b1001U0Z40zIOHKLLM9","sessionID":"ses_158954ac9ffePahLx5YfsvlJLH","messageID":"msg_ea76be466001gwQJbddIXqivKi"}}
