{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1780925425137,"sessionID":"ses_158954ac9ffePahLx5YfsvlJLH","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_KI8DoBrbyvRuXlY1REkeTpz4","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/OpenLtm-main/docs/04-configuration.md","offset":1,"limit":120},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/OpenLtm-main/docs/04-configuration.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: # Configuration\n2: \n3: Configure via `~/.claude/config.json`.\n4: \n5: ## LTM options\n6: \n7: ```json\n8: {\n9:   \"ltm\": {\n10:     \"dbPath\": \"$CLAUDE_PLUGIN_DATA/openltm.db\",\n11:     \"decayEnabled\": true,\n12:     \"injectTopN\": 15,\n13:     \"autoRelate\": true,\n14:     \"graphReasoning\": false,\n15:     \"evaluateSessionLlm\": false,\n16:     \"semanticFallback\": true\n17:   }\n18: }\n19: ```\n20: \n21: | Key | Default | Description |\n22: |-----|---------|-------------|\n23: | `dbPath` | auto-resolved | Override db location (prefer `LTM_DB_PATH` env var) |\n24: | `decayEnabled` | `true` | Enable memory relevance decay over time |\n25: | `injectTopN` | `15` | Max memories to inject at SessionStart |\n26: | `autoRelate` | `true` | Automatically link related memories |\n27: | `graphReasoning` | `false` | Enable graph-based reasoning during recall |\n28: | `evaluateSessionLlm` | `false` | Use LLM to evaluate sessions (costs tokens) |\n29: | `semanticFallback` | `true` | Fall back to embedding search when FTS returns no results |\n30: \n31: ## DB path\n32: \n33: Three ways to set it (priority order):\n34: \n35: 1. **`LTM_DB_PATH` env var** — set in your shell profile for a permanent override\n36: 2. **`CLAUDE_PLUGIN_DATA`** — set automatically by the plugin system on marketplace installs\n37: 3. **Default fallback** — `$CLAUDE_PLUGIN_DATA/openltm.db`\n38: \n39: ```bash\n40: # Shell override example\n41: export LTM_DB_PATH=/custom/path/openltm.db\n42: ```\n43: \n44: ## Server options\n45: \n46: ```json\n47: {\n48:   \"server\": {\n49:     \"apiPort\": 7331,\n50:     \"uiPort\": 7332\n51:   }\n52: }\n53: ```\n54: \n55: The graph API runs on `apiPort`, the Next.js UI on `uiPort`.\n56: \n57: ## Sync (experimental)\n58: \n59: ```json\n60: {\n61:   \"sync\": {\n62:     \"enabled\": false,\n63:     \"provider\": \"s3\"\n64:   }\n65: }\n66: ```\n67: \n68: Providers: `s3` | `r2` | `null`\n69: \n70: ## Per-project settings (optional)\n71: \n72: Create `.claude/ltm.local.md` in your project for per-project LTM overrides:\n73: \n74: ```markdown\n75: ---\n76: enabled: true\n77: injectTopN: 10\n78: autoRecall: false\n79: ---\n80: \n81: # Project-specific notes\n82: \n83: This project uses stricter memory injection.\n84: ```\n85: \n86: **Fields:**\n87: - `enabled` — Enable/disable LTM for this project (default: true)\n88: - `injectTopN` — Override max memories to inject\n89: - `autoRecall` — Override auto-recall at session start\n90: \n91: **Note:** Changes require restarting Claude Code.\n\n(End of file - total 91 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"# Configuration\n\nConfigure via `~/.claude/config.json`.\n\n## LTM options\n\n```json\n{\n  \"ltm\": {\n    \"dbPath\": \"$CLAUDE_PLUGIN_DATA/openltm.db\",\n    \"decayEnabled\": true,\n    \"injectTopN\": 15,\n    \"autoRelate\": true,\n    \"graphReasoning\": false,\n    \"evaluateSessionLlm\": false,\n    \"semanticFallback\": true\n  }\n}\n```\n","truncated":false,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/OpenLtm-main/docs/04-configuration.md","text":"# Configuration\n\nConfigure via `~/.claude/config.json`.\n\n## LTM options\n\n```json\n{\n  \"ltm\": {\n    \"dbPath\": \"$CLAUDE_PLUGIN_DATA/openltm.db\",\n    \"decayEnabled\": true,\n    \"injectTopN\": 15,\n    \"autoRelate\": true,\n    \"graphReasoning\": false,\n    \"evaluateSessionLlm\": false,\n    \"semanticFallback\": true\n  }\n}\n```\n\n| Key | Default | Description |\n|-----|---------|-------------|\n| `dbPath` | auto-resolved | Override db location (prefer `LTM_DB_PATH` env var) |\n| `decayEnabled` | `true` | Enable memory relevance decay over time |\n| `injectTopN` | `15` | Max memories to inject at SessionStart |\n| `autoRelate` | `true` | Automatically link related memories |\n| `graphReasoning` | `false` | Enable graph-based reasoning during recall |\n| `evaluateSessionLlm` | `false` | Use LLM to evaluate sessions (costs tokens) |\n| `semanticFallback` | `true` | Fall back to embedding search when FTS returns no results |\n\n## DB path\n\nThree ways to set it (priority order):\n\n1. **`LTM_DB_PATH` env var** — set in your shell profile for a permanent override\n2. **`CLAUDE_PLUGIN_DATA`** — set automatically by the plugin system on marketplace installs\n3. **Default fallback** — `$CLAUDE_PLUGIN_DATA/openltm.db`\n\n```bash\n# Shell override example\nexport LTM_DB_PATH=/custom/path/openltm.db\n```\n\n## Server options\n\n```json\n{\n  \"server\": {\n    \"apiPort\": 7331,\n    \"uiPort\": 7332\n  }\n}\n```\n\nThe graph API runs on `apiPort`, the Next.js UI on `uiPort`.\n\n## Sync (experimental)\n\n```json\n{\n  \"sync\": {\n    \"enabled\": false,\n    \"provider\": \"s3\"\n  }\n}\n```\n\nProviders: `s3` | `r2` | `null`\n\n## Per-project settings (optional)\n\nCreate `.claude/ltm.local.md` in your project for per-project LTM overrides:\n\n```markdown\n---\nenabled: true\ninjectTopN: 10\nautoRecall: false\n---\n\n# Project-specific notes\n\nThis project uses stricter memory injection.\n```\n\n**Fields:**\n- `enabled` — Enable/disable LTM for this project (default: true)\n- `injectTopN` — Override max memories to inject\n- `autoRecall` — Override auto-recall at session start\n\n**Note:** Changes require restarting Claude Code.","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":91,"totalLines":91,"truncated":false}},"title":"specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/OpenLtm-main/docs/04-configuration.md","time":{"start":1780925425121,"end":1780925425132}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_0fae45739a0d6330016a26c3f09f54819191714403851dc00d"}},"id":"prt_ea76d6412001cw7GT7Uam3f2Wd","sessionID":"ses_158954ac9ffePahLx5YfsvlJLH","messageID":"msg_ea76d502b001eBkNzNO9CIsVB4"}}
{"type":"step_finish","timestamp":1780925425791,"sessionID":"ses_158954ac9ffePahLx5YfsvlJLH","part":{"id":"prt_ea76d687b001ARWSB6z50BQ1qM","reason":"tool-calls","snapshot":"9eb759036c70dfaf48052a0874ef0dc2063d2098","messageID":"msg_ea76d502b001eBkNzNO9CIsVB4","sessionID":"ses_158954ac9ffePahLx5YfsvlJLH","type":"step-finish","tokens":{"total":95280,"input":986,"output":70,"reasoning":16,"cache":{"write":0,"read":94208}},"cost":0}}
{"type":"step_start","timestamp":1780925428184,"sessionID":"ses_158954ac9ffePahLx5YfsvlJLH","part":{"id":"prt_ea76d71d6001HrIgA2oUw3qB7c","messageID":"msg_ea76d69c6001OKo41tcT6TL2om","sessionID":"ses_158954ac9ffePahLx5YfsvlJLH","snapshot":"00b291ebea3c5e00cd57a53cd03e32f7390e20f8","type":"step-start"}}
{"type":"text","timestamp":1780925545568,"sessionID":"ses_158954ac9ffePahLx5YfsvlJLH","part":{"id":"prt_ea76ebd9d001QeXjaQzYLOByZ8","messageID":"msg_ea76d69c6001OKo41tcT6TL2om","sessionID":"ses_158954ac9ffePahLx5YfsvlJLH","type":"text","text":"## Mechanism\nOpenLTM’s janitor is an explicit sequential pass guarded against concurrent runs, with per-stage error capture and run-result counters (`packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/index.ts:51`, `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/index.ts:52`, `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/index.ts:74`, `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/index.ts:116`). The order is embed missing memories, decay, archive, promote, then dedup-stage (`packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/index.ts:75`, `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/index.ts:82`, `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/index.ts:89`, `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/index.ts:96`, `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/index.ts:103`). It persists last-run counters in `settings`, seeded by migration 012, then runs WAL checkpoint and `ANALYZE` hygiene (`packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/index.ts:130`, `migrations/012_seed_janitor_settings.sql:5`, `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/index.ts:139`).\n\nScheduling is optional: `ltm.janitor.intervalMinutes` defaults to `0`, so auto-run is disabled unless configured (`packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/providers/types.ts:140`, `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/index.ts:183`, `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/index.ts:189`). A separate Honker scheduler defines `@every 6h`, leader-elected enqueue, worker claim/retry, and inert fallback when Honker is unavailable; actual server startup wiring is UNKNOWN from the scoped files (`packages/openltm-core/src/scheduler/index.ts:18`, `packages/openltm-core/src/scheduler/index.ts:10`, `packages/openltm-core/src/scheduler/index.ts:61`, `packages/openltm-core/src/scheduler/index.ts:75`).\n\nEmbedding maintenance uses a `memory_embeddings` side table with model/dim metadata and optional vec0 dual-write (`migrations/010_memory_embeddings_split.sql:5`, `packages/openltm-core/src/dao/embeddings.ts:36`, `packages/openltm-core/src/dao/embeddings.ts:48`). The janitor asks for up to 10,000 missing IDs and embeds batches of 50 by default (`packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/embeddings.ts:86`, `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/embeddings.ts:92`, `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/embeddings.ts:107`). Caveat: the missing-ID DAO filters only `status='active'`, while the later fetch allows active/pending, so pending proposal embedding is effectively UNKNOWN/active-only (`packages/openltm-core/src/dao/embeddings.ts:69`, `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/embeddings.ts:99`).\n\nDecay is materialized: migration 011 adds indexed `decay_score`, and recall uses `ORDER BY decay_score DESC` for default relevance (`migrations/011_add_decay_score_and_archive.sql:4`, `migrations/011_add_decay_score_and_archive.sql:6`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:524`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:526`). The formula is `importance * confidence * 0.5^(age/half_life)`, except importance 5 and `confirm_count >= 10` do not age-decay; half-lives are 180/90/30/14 days for importance 4/3/2/else (`packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/decay.ts:14`, `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/decay.ts:17`, `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/decay.ts:20`, `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/decay.ts:22`, `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/decay.ts:24`, `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/decay.ts:26`). Deprecation triggers at `importance < 5`, `confirm_count < 10`, and `decay_score < 0.25`; archive later evicts only deprecated, importance <=2, recall_count <=1, score <0.10, max 100/run, preserving JSON first (`packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/decay.ts:31`, `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/archive.ts:4`, `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/archive.ts:17`, `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/archive.ts:49`).\n\nPromotion scans active unlinked `context_items` of type decision/gotcha with content >20 chars, dedups by normalized key, then creates `status='pending'` memories with source `auto-promote`, confidence 0.8, architecture/gotcha category, gotcha importance 4, and decision importance default 3 (`packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/promote.ts:51`, `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/promote.ts:64`, `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/promote.ts:83`, `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/promote.ts:89`, `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/providers/types.ts:139`). Approval flips pending to active; rejection deletes the pending memory and resets the context item (`packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/promote.ts:112`, `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/promote.ts:122`, `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/promote.ts:134`, `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/promote.ts:146`). Dedup intends pairwise active-memory cosine matching at 0.85 plus optional LLM JSON verdict, then saves pending `dedup:idA:idB` proposals; however it still selects `memories.embedding` even though migration 010 drops that column, so the current dedup pass appears schema-stale (`packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/dedup.ts:73`, `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/dedup.ts:90`, `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/dedup.ts:114`, `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/dedup.ts:160`, `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/dedup.ts:211`, `migrations/010_memory_embeddings_split.sql:24`).\n\n## Teachings for system-spec-kit\n- **Claim** · Add a low-frequency maintenance report, not a replacement for the self-maintaining index · **Evidence** · `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/index.ts:130`, `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/index.ts:139` · **Maps-to** · `memory_health`, `memory_index_scan`, `memory_embedding_reconcile` · **Verdict** · ADAPT · **Risk** · LOW · **Confidence** · 0.88 · **Why it transfers (or not)** · Our incremental index is better for freshness, but explicit last-run counters and hygiene summaries improve operator trust.\n- **Claim** · Introduce a pending promotion tier for mined continuity insights before durable memory admission · **Evidence** · `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/promote.ts:51`, `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/promote.ts:89` · **Maps-to** · shadow feedback reducers or new sub-packet · **Verdict** · ADOPT · **Risk** · MED · **Confidence** · 0.86 · **Why it transfers (or not)** · Single-user does not remove quality risk; review-before-activation fits our spec ladder and FSRS can score after approval.\n- **Claim** · Stage semantic dedup as proposals, never auto-merge memory records · **Evidence** · `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/index.ts:103`, `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/dedup.ts:211` · **Maps-to** · new dedup proposal queue plus causal-edge preservation · **Verdict** · ADOPT · **Risk** · LOW · **Confidence** · 0.90 · **Why it transfers (or not)** · Our causal edges make destructive merge riskier; staged review preserves lineage.\n- **Claim** · Do not copy OpenLTM’s decay formula; adapt only stale-candidate reporting · **Evidence** · `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/decay.ts:17`, `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/archive.ts:4` · **Maps-to** · FSRS decay, retention sweep · **Verdict** · ADAPT · **Risk** · MED · **Confidence** · 0.82 · **Why it transfers (or not)** · FSRS/co-activation is richer than fixed half-lives, but archive-style candidates could aid audits.\n- **Claim** · Treat embedding/dedup schema drift as a warning for separate vector stores · **Evidence** · `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/dedup.ts:90`, `migrations/010_memory_embeddings_split.sql:24` · **Maps-to** · `memory_embedding_reconcile` tests · **Verdict** · ADOPT · **Risk** · MED · **Confidence** · 0.84 · **Why it transfers (or not)** · Our separate vector store has the same drift class, so reconciliation tests matter more than janitor cleverness.\n- **Claim** · Defer leader-elected cron complexity · **Evidence** · `packages/openltm-core/src/scheduler/index.ts:53`, `packages/openltm-core/src/scheduler/index.ts:61` · **Maps-to** · daemon scheduling/new sub-packet · **Verdict** · DEFER · **Risk** · MED · **Confidence** · 0.79 · **Why it transfers (or not)** · Local single-user system-spec-kit usually needs coalesced maintenance, not distributed cron ownership.\n\n## Negative knowledge\nDo not copy fixed half-life decay as the primary relevance model; FSRS plus co-activation is more expressive. Do not copy O(n²) all-pairs dedup as-is; use vector top-K/proposal staging. Do not hard-archive spec continuity by simple score thresholds; governed retention and provenance should dominate. Do not adopt Honker-style scheduling unless we first prove current self-maintenance leaves stale work.\n\n## Open questions\nShould system-spec-kit expose a first-class `pending_memory_proposals` review surface? Should dedup proposals preserve causal edges as `supports`/`supersedes` candidates instead of merges? Should maintenance reporting be a dry-run janitor dashboard over existing tools rather than a new writer?","time":{"start":1780925513117,"end":1780925545561},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"msg_0fa2bcfce73da8e0016a26c44914f4819181302945e40fe32d","phase":"final_answer"}}}}
